  "response": "To determine the equations for final velocity, you'll need to use kinematic equations based on the specific scenario and given information. Here are the key approaches:\n\n1. Basic Kinematic Equations:\nv = v\u2080 + at\nWhere:\nv = Final velocity\nv\u2080 = Initial velocity\na = Acceleration\nt = Time\n\n2. When Displacement is Known:\nv\u00b2 = v\u2080\u00b2 + 2a(\u0394x)\nWhere:\nv = Final velocity\nv\u2080 = Initial velocity\na = Acceleration\n\u0394x = Displacement\n\n3. Key Considerations:\n- Identify known variables\n- Select appropriate equation\n- Consider direction of motion\n- Account for initial conditions\n\n4. Special Cases:\n- Free fall\n- Constant acceleration\n- Projectile motion\n\n5. Additional Information Needed:\n- Initial velocity\n- Acceleration\n- Time or displacement\n- Direction of motion\n\nThe specific equation used depends on:\n- Available information\n- Problem constraints\n- Type of motion (linear, circular, etc.)\n\nAlways carefully analyze the problem and select the most appropriate kinematic equation.",
